 The Infinite-Scale Solution: Router + Tool RegistriesTo build a system that works flawlessly whether you have 3 tools or 300 tools, you use a Two-Tier Router Architecture. Instead of forcing your main LLM to look at every single tool you own, you break your tools into separate Modules (e.g., System Module, Fitbit Module, general Chat Module).Telegram User Prompt ➡️ 🗂️ Step 1: Tiny Intent Router (Categorizes the prompt)
                                            /        |        \
                             [System Module]  [Fitbit Module]  [General Chat]

                                   |                 |                |
                       (Only 5 System Tools) (Only 5 Fitbit Tools) (Hits Redis Tools)


How it works under the hood:The Traffic Cop: When you send a message, a super-fast, tiny local model (like llama3.2:1b) reads it and picks a general bucket: "SYSTEM", "FITBIT", or "GENERAL".Dynamic Injecting:If it says "FITBIT", your code pulls your Fitbit tools out of a python file and hands only those specific tools to Ollama.If it says "GENERAL", it bypasses tools entirely and looks up the answer in your Redis Semantic Cache.💻 The Future-Proof Implementation StrategyYou can organize this directly in your Python bot project directory using a clean folder layout:textmy_telegram_bot/
│
├── bot.py             # Main Telegram loop & Intent Router
├── config.py          # Redis cache settings
│
└── tools/             # Where you add new features without breaking old ones
    ├── system.py      # Contains get_uptime(), get_disk_space()
    ├── fitbit.py      # Contains get_steps(), get_sleep_data()
    └── smart_home.py  # Contains toggle_lights(), set_thermostat()





    
